616    /**
617    * Scans for the next node, starting at the specified point, and using 'previous'
618    * as a hint that the last node we returned was 'previous' (so we know not to return
619    * it again). If 'tree' is non-null, this will limit the search to the given tree.
620    *
621    * The basic premise is that each iteration can follow the following steps:
622    *
623    * 1) Scan all the way to the left.
624    * a) If we already started from this node last time, proceed to Step 2.
625    * b) If a valid uplink is found, use it.
626    * c) If the result is an empty node (root not set), break the scan.
627    * d) If we already returned the left node, break the scan.
628    *
629    * 2) Check the right.
630    * a) If we already returned the right node, proceed to Step 3.
631    * b) If it is a valid uplink, use it.
632    * c) Do Step 1 from the right node.
633    *
634    * 3) Back up through the parents until we encounter find a parent
635    * that we're not the right child of.
636    *
637    * 4) If there's no right child of that parent, the iteration is finished.
638    * Otherwise continue to Step 5.
639    *
640    * 5) Check to see if the right child is a valid uplink.
641    * a) If we already returned that child, proceed to Step 6.
642    * Otherwise, use it.
643    *
644    * 6) If the right child of the parent is the parent itself, we've
645    * already found & returned the end of the Trie, so exit.
646    *
647    * 7) Do Step 1 on the parent's right child.
648    */
